-top|countable: any particular variety of cheese}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|quesu|m}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt|yue|芝士|tr=zi1 si6-2}}\n*: Hokkien: {{tt|nan-hbl|chhì-juh}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|乾酪|tr=gānlào}}, {{tt+|cmn|乳酪|tr=rǔlào}}, {{tt+|cmn|奶酪|tr=nǎilào}}, {{tt+|cmn|芝士|tr=zhīshì}}, {{tt+|cmn|起司|tr=qǐsī}}, {{tt+|cmn|起士|tr=qǐshì}}, {{tt+|cmn|吉士|tr=jíshì}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|sýr|m}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|ost|c}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|juust}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|ostur|m}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|juusto}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|fromage|m}}\n*: Old French: {{tt|fro|furmage|m}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Käse|m}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|τυρί|n}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt+|mk|сирење|n}}\n* Manx: {{tt|gv|caashey|m}}\n* Norman: {{tt|nrf|fronmage|m}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|ost|m}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|ost|m}}\n* Old English: {{tt|ang|ċīese|m}}\n* Pashto: {{tt+|ps|پوڅه|f|tr=poča}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|queijo|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|сыр|m}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|syr|m}}\n* Somali: {{tt|so|farmaajo}}\n* Sotho: {{tt|st|ditjhese}}, {{tt|st|tjhese}}\n* Swahili: {{tt+|sw|chizi}}, {{tt+|sw|jibini}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|ost|c}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|peynir}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|پنیر|tr=penir}}\n* Uzbek: {{tt+|uz|pishloq}}\n* Venetan: {{tt+|vec|formai|m}}, {{tt+|vec|formajo|m}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|caws|m}}, {{tt|cy|cosyn|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|slang: money}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|chechtáky|p}}, {{tt+|cs|prachy}}, {{tt+|cs|love}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|hillo}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|fric|m}}, {{tt+|fr|pognon|m}}, {{tt+|fr|flouze|m}}, {{tt+|fr|oseille|f}}, {{tt+|fr|tune|f}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|grana|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|grana|f}}, {{tt+|pt|bufunfa|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|slang: fastball in baseball}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|ストレート|tr=sutorēto}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{pedia}}\n* {{pedia|Cheese (recreational drug)}}\n* {{l|en|butter}}\n* {{l|en|cream}}\n* {{l|en|milk}}\n* {{l|en|turophile}}\n* {{l|en|yogurt}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# To prepare [[curds]] for making cheese.\n# {{lb|en|technology}} To make holes in a pattern of circuitry to decrease pattern density.\n# {{lb|en|slang}} To smile excessively, as for a camera.\n#* {{quote-song|en|author=[[w:Open Mike Eagle|Michael W. Eagle II]]|artist=Open Mike Eagle; Busdriver|title=Degrassi Picture Day|album=Sir Rockabye|year=2013|track=1|passage=Yeah, a couple homegirls '''cheese''' they little faces off / They happy cause they finally got they braces off}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|author=w:Doja Cat|title=Doja Cat - Say So (Official Video)|date=February 27, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227213211/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pok8H_KF1FA|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pok8H_KF1FA|time=00:42|archivedate=February 27, 2020|passage=It's been a long time since you fell in love / You ain't coming out your shell, you ain't really been yourself / Tell me, what must I do? (Do tell, my love) / 'Cause luckily I'm good at reading / I wouldn't bug him, but he won't stop '''cheesin''''}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2020|author={{w|Bryan Washington}}|title=[[w:Memorial (novel)|Memorial]]|publisher=Atlantic Books (2021)|page=189|passage=Now Kunihiko sprinted back up the stairs. Exploded through the bar with three sacks of convenience store chicken, '''cheesing''' from ear to ear.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|cheese up}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nPerhaps an alteration of {{m|en|cheers}}.\n\n====Interjection====\n{{en-intj|head=!}}\n\n# {{lb|en|photography}} {{non-gloss|Said while being photographed, to give the impression of smiling.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Say \"'''cheese'''\"! ... and there we are!}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|say cheese}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|is|sís|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ja|チーズ|tr=chīzu|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ko|치즈|bor=1}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|said while being photographed}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Basque: {{t|eu|txakoli}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|зеле}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|Lluís}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt|yue|一二三}} {{q|lit. 1, 2, 3; said by person taking the photograph}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|茄子|tr=qiézi}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|sýr}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|appelsin}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|muikku}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|ouistiti}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Spaghetti}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|גבינה|tr=g'viná}}\n* Hindi: {{tt+|hi|पनीर}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|csíz}}\n* Irish: {{tt|ga|abair aoibh}}, {{tt|ga|abair grian}}, {{tt|ga|abair cáis}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|チーズ|tr=chīzu}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|김치}}, {{t+|ko|치즈}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|سیب|tr=sib}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|ser|m}}, {{t+|pl|uśmiech|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|xis}}, {{tt+|pt|giz}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|сыр}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|пти̏чица|f}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|ptȉčica|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|patata}}, {{tt+|es|whisky}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|omelett}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|peynir}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|hai}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nThough commonly claimed to be a borrowing of {{bor|en|fa|چیز|tr=čiz|t=thing}}, the term does not occur earliest in Anglo-Indian sources, but instead is \"well recorded in British and Australian sources from the 1840s onwards\".<ref>James Lambert, 2018, 'Anglo-Indian slang in dictionaries on historical principles' ''World Englishes'' Vol. 37, page 255. [https://doi.org/10.1111/weng.12291]</ref>\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|slang}} Wealth, fame, excellence, importance.\n# {{lb|en|slang|dated|British India}} The correct thing, of excellent quality; the [[ticket]].\n#: {{ux|en|These [[cheroot]]s are the real '''cheese'''.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|big cheese}}\n* {{l|en|sub-cheese}}\n\n====References====\n<references/>\n\n===Etymology 4===\n{{unk|en|title=Etymology unknown}}. Possibly an alteration of {{m|en|cease}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|slang}} To stop; to refrain from.\n#: {{ux|en|'''Cheese''' it! The cops!}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Cheese''' your patter! ''({{=}} stop talking, shut up)''}}\n# {{lb|en|slang}} To [[anger]] or irritate someone, usually in combination with \"off\".\n#: {{ux|en|All this waiting around is really '''cheesing''' me off.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|cheese it}}\n* {{l|en|cheesed off}}\n\n===Etymology 5===\nFrom {{m|en|cheesy}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|gaming}} The exploitation, or opportunity for exploitation, of an unintentional [[video game]] [[mechanic]].\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|Internet slang|gaming|ambitransitive}} To use a controversial or [[unsporting]] [[tactic]] to gain an advantage (especially in a game.)\n#: {{ux|en|You can '''cheese''' most of the game using certain exploits.}}\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|year=1993|author=Alex Werner|newsgroup=alt.games.sf2|url=https://groups.google.com/g/alt.games.sf2/c/URh2GTbZvTc/m/vsMceclgkB0J|passage=The term '''cheesing''' is also pretty common. However, at least originally, ticking had a more specific meaning, ie hitting someone and then throwing after they block, whereas '''cheesing''' would be anything \"cheap\", and thereore depended on the user [...]}}\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|year=2000|author=cyber...@my-deja.com|newsgroup=rec.games.miniatures.warhammer|url=https://groups.google.com/g/rec.games.miniatures.warhammer/c/VEHh5n8iGWY/m/UnpaoBHPsM4J|passage=The moral of the story is, real strategy doesn't apply in WH40K. Find out where your opponent '''cheesed''' himself up and hit him there with everything you've got.}}\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|year=2001|author=Samiel|newsgroup=rec.sport.billiard|url=https://groups.google.com/g/rec.sport.billiard/c/wTgZwxjBNDo/m/2xJb0-06A08J|passage=\"'''Cheesing'''\" means to shoot for the 9-ball (in 9-ball) before being on the 9-ball (i.e. shooting at the 1-ball to hit the 9-ball in). Basically if you can do it, you'll win the game (but perhaps not much respect).}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2008|author=Reed Stevens; Tom Satwicz; Laurie McCarthy|title=In-Game, In-Room, In-World: Reconnecting Video Game Play to the Rest of Kids’ Lives|work=The Ecology of Games: Connecting Youth, Games, and Learning|series=The John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation Series on Digital Media and Learning|location=Cambridge, MA|publisher=The MIT Press|editor=Katie Salen|page=54|doi=10.1162/dmal.9780262693646.041|text=For example, he was accused of \"cheating\" when he modified his in-game play techniques—without the use of cheat codes—but in ways that were unexpected to his opponents. Taking these actions (called '''cheesing''' by some in game play discourse) was unexpected, because the actions diverged from courses of action perceived as normal in the real-world activity the game simulated.}}\n# {{lb|en|video games|slang}} To use an [[unconventional]], [[all-in]] strategy to take one's opponent by surprise early in the game (especially for [[real-time strategy]] games).\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|use a surprise all-in strategy early in a game}} {{l|en|rush}}, {{l|en|zerg}}\n* {{l|en|gamebreaking}}\n\n{{C|en|Cheeses|Dairy products}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA|tchize}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|informal}} {{clipping of|fr|cheeseburger}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|chese}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|enm|verb|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|chesen}}"}}